                         STARTING WITH C

This is the first of a short series of articles about the shareware C compiler
on disk LAN.05 (from now on called for short MJC, after its author Mark
Johnson). Its aimed at filling the gap between the documentation supplied with
MJC, and the general C texts - usually not compiler or machine specific -
available in the bookshops. Over the series I'll be covering the hardware
configuration you need to run MJC, an editing  and compiling environment to
run it in, and how to extend it for missing GEM calls, for A-line graphics
(sprites) and for access to the BIOS/XBIOS/GEMDOS;  plus a few other bits and
pieces. Steve tells me he receives queries about MJC from members trying to
make a start with C - in fact he's passed a couple on to me - and I shall bear
it in mind that MJC is often acquired by people new both to the ST and C, and
hopefully cover the ground accordingly. There will be a disc C.07 to accompany
the series containing all the software mentioned in it - space permitting  -
and I'll describe its format and content as I go along.  However this isn't a
complete tutorial in C programming and I shall assume that the reader has
access to ( at least ) 'A Book on C' by Berry and Meekings, which is the basis
of disks C.01 to C.03. A good - and cheap - reference book I rely on myself is
'Lexicon of C' by Alex Ragen (Sigma Press, ś11.95). There are literally dozens
of books in print on 'C' programming, so a visit to a good bookshop is highly
recommended.

First, the hardware. One of MJC's biggest plus points - outside its price, of
course - is the fact that it will run well on a standard old-style 520STFM (ie
512k of RAM and a single-sided disk). All of the commercial compilers, when
set up for this, thrash the disk drive and run slow. But I do think you need
80 columns to do any worthwhile programming; in fact I switched to the ST for
just that reason. The high-res mono monitor is perfect of course, but I myself
find medium-res colour perfectly acceptable; and if you're really broke you
can look in Practical Electronics/Wireless World/Micro Computer Mart for a
cheap composite mono monitor, which is noticeably more readable than a TV.

On to the software environment, and that user-friendly interface you bought
the ST for. Sorry, but its got to go - real programmers like you and me work
down on the bare metal. The GEM interface is perfect for running applications,
but not very good for developing them. You're going to have to use the
keyboard to edit your program source and supply the arguments to the compiler
and suchlike; as serious word-processor users find, it soon gets boring
dodging between keyboard and mouse. Apart from anything else you'll find it
impossible to read the error messages from the compiler before they're wiped
out by GEM renewing the desktop - and I guarantee you will get error
messages.

The alternative way of doing things is with what MS-DOS and Commodore call a
CLI (Command Line Interpreter) and UNIX calls a shell; since UNIX is all the
rage right now, and most C textbooks talk UNIX, I'll call it a shell. There
are several shells for the ST available in the public domain, ranging from the
simple to the downright amazing - Gulaam on UTL.20 falls into the amazing
category - but for our purposes on a half-meg ST I don't think COMMAND.TOS,
the shell supplied with MJC, can be beaten. Its bomb-free, compact (17k),
allows shell scripts (batch files) and can be extended without the joins
showing. By this I mean it doesn't need the filename extension to be supplied
with a command. If for example you type
      edit fred.c [return]
the shell will first check whether edit is one of its own built-in commands  -
it isn't - and then go on to search for a shell script called edit.bat, then a
GEM program called edit.prg, and then a TOS program called edit.ttp. This sort
of seamless extension makes the creation of an integrated environment for
editing, compiling and testing programs a doddle. In fact the main drawback to
COMMAND is the lack of documentation; I've got three versions of it with
different names from different sources, but all came without a manual - so if
anyone out there has one I would appreciate a copy. As a stop-gap I've
included a list of the commands and what I think they do, together with some
examples, in the DOCS directory on C.07.

Before going on to describe how to use the compiler, a few words about the C
language itself. Despite first appearances, C is  a very simple language - or,
to be honest, "simple if you like it, crude if you don't".  It has a limited
range of data types but a comprehensive set of operators to manipulate them;
it has a good set  of facilities for program structure and flow control ( if
for do while switch etc. ); and its good at calling other modules. In fact it
has to be, because that's just about all it can do. I suspect the major hurdle
people face when moving from BASIC to C is that C contains no commands, in the
BASIC sense of the word. To actually do something in C means calling a library
routine, and apart from a limited subset these routines differ from compiler
to compiler and machine to machine.

There are two libraries supplied with MJC. LIB.A contains the standard C
library routines for file handling, for input and output, and for string
handling. LIB.DOC in the LIBS folder on LAN.05 covers these routines, which
are described in all the standard C texts - see for example chapter 3 of 'A
Book on C'. GEM.A contains the routines - or at least some of them - for
creating GEM applications; for example window and event handling, graphics
commands, and alert and menu processing. The major documentation supplied with
MJC for this library is the source listing ( GEM.C ), which is certainly
comprehensive but not always comprehensible, at least to the beginner. If you
intend to write GEM programs you will need one of the GEM-specific manuals
such as 'The GEM Programmers Reference' from Abacus, or 'Atari ST Application
Programming' from Bantam.
I haven't had time to test these routines exhaustively, but the 2.1 version of
LIB.A has been greatly extended when compared to 1.0 and corresponds far more
closely to the 'standard' - the standard in this case being K & R ( 'The C
Programming Language' by Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie, who invented it
). The GEM library still contains holes, and the LIBRARY.SRC folder on C.07
contains a version of GEM.C with some corrections and additions by me.

There is another set of functions available on the ST that I've had queries
about. It isn't immediately apparent looking at MJC how to invoke the
BIOS/XBIOS/GEMDOS functions, as described in 'Atari ST Internals' etc. The
author catered for this by building a 'trap' command into the language. As a
simple example, the GEMDOS function Tgetdate() - which predictably enough
returns the date - is invoked in assembler by the instructions
    move #$2a,-sp        [put function no. on stack
    trap #1              [call GEMDOS
In MJC, this can be done by:
    date = trap( 1, 0x2a);     /* get date */
but made more readable by creating a header file with:
    #define Tgetdate() trap(1,0x2a)
and in the program writing:
    date = Tgetdate();
The header file OSBIND.H on the 2.1 disk contains a set of definitions like
this for the TOS functions. However I have had one or two problems with this,
due I think to the way MJC handles macro expansion, so I've left an
alternative version which I used with 1.0 on C.07. It still hasn't been
exhaustively checked or tested, so feedback will be appreciated.

