Put the disk in your drive and switch on. The hiccup at the start is a
reset-proof 180k RAM disk being set up, followed by a switch to 60Hz screen
update which gives (on a medium resolution monitor) a clearer picture and less
eyestrain. The desktop should appear with two disk windows open, one for drive
A showing COMMAND2.TOS, one for drive D (the RAM disk) showing it empty.

Double-click on COMMAND2.TOS in the drive A window. (I've never been able to
spot any difference between COMMAND and COMMAND2; I use it simply because I
assume it's a later version ). The desktop will disappear, and you'll get a
prompt thus A>. This means drive A is your current default drive, and the
shell is waiting for a command.
Type 'coldgo' and press return. ( what you actually type is between the
quotes; I'm putting them in only to separate the commands from the description
bit - and from now on I won't mention pressing 'return' ). This causes the
shell to read in the shell script COLDGO.BAT from the current drive and
execute the commands in it. These are:
    copy a:\compiler\*.* d:
    copy a:\libs\*.* d:
    path d:;a:\;a:\utilitie.s;a:;
    show a:
    show d:
    cd %1
and its probably worth explaining what they do.

Line 1 copies the contents of the directory called "compiler" on drive A into
drive D (the RAM disk). It does this using a 'wild card' for the filename: "*"
will replace any group of characters in a filename, so "*.*" means any file
with any extension ie any file at all. Since the RAM disk is reset-proof ( ie
the only way to get rid of it is to switch off your machine ), if you lock up
the system by test-running a duff program you will be able to recover by
simply pressing the warm reset button on the back of the ST; in this case
restart by the command 'warmgo', which misses out this line because the files
are already in the RAM disk.

Line 2 does the same as 1 for directory LIBS.

Line 3 uses the path command to specify where the shell is to look for any
programs or scripts it is asked to execute. The ";" is a separator, so the
command actually says:-
    first try the ram disk (D:)
    next try the root directory on the boot disk (A:\)
    then try the utilities directory on the boot disk (A:\UTILITIE.S)
    finally try the current working directory on the boot disk (A:)

Lines 4 and 5 are informative; they display the free space left on the two
discs.

Line 6 is normally used to define the current working directory. For example,
if you were working on a program in directory "page", you would type 'coldgo
page' and the shell would substitute "page" where "%1" appears in the script;
but in this case, where the argument is left out, cd will simply display the
current directory ( the root directory "\" ).

The program we're going to write and test is a version of the UNIX utility
'cat' - nothing to do with pets, its short for con-cat-enate - and not quite
the same as the version supplied with the L.05 disk. I've chosen it because a)
its short b) its useful c) its a nice example of file-handling and i-o
redirection and d) since its mostly cribbed from messrs. K & R (above), it
should be an example of good programming practice. Cat accepts as arguments a
row of n filenames ( where n is in the range 0-30 ) and writes the contents of
those files to the 'standard output'. If n is 0 ( ie you don't supply any
filenames ) cat gets its data from 'standard input'. All this is tied into the
relationship between C and UNIX, and probably bears explaining. When you
create a .ttp program with MJC ( other Cs are similar ) the compiler generates
code to open three default files: standard input, standard output and standard
error. Standard input is normally connected to the keyboard, and standard
output and error to the screen. So, for example:-
     cat              on its own as a command doesn't do a lot - what you
                      type in on the keyboard (standard input) appears on
                      the screen (standard output).
     cat fred         where 'fred' is the name of a file, acts as a show
                      command; the file is displayed on the screen.
This starts to get interesting when you add 'redirection'. This again is a
facility handled by the compiler - you don't have to do anything in your
program. The symbols < and > followed by a filename redirect standard input
and output respectively; not forgetting that "aux:" and "prt:" are filenames
referring to the serial and printer ports, that if you redirect to a
nonexistent file it will be created, and that you can add to (rather than
overwrite) a file by using >> instead of >. So:-
     cat >prt:            emulates a typewriter; what you type in is
                          routed to the printer.
     cat fred >prt:       prints file fred.
     cat fred >jim        copies fred to jim (creating jim if necessary).
     cat >jim             creates jim, and copies into it what you type
                          following the command ( control/d to finish ).
     cat fred jim >d:joe  creates joe on drive D, copies fred to it,
                          and appends jim to the end.
Not bad for 20 or so lines of code! - and here they are.
-------------------------------------------------------------------
#include <stdio.h>
main(argc,argv) int argc; char *argv[];
{
int c;
FILE *fp,*fopen();
     if (argc==1)
        {   while (( c=getc(stdin) ) != 0x04)
             putc(c,stdout);    }
     else
        while(--argc > 0)
          if (( fp=fopen(*++argv, "r") ) == NULL)
             {    fprintf(stderr,"cat: can't open %s\n",*argv);
               return(1);       }
          else
          {    while ( (c=getc(fp)) != EOF)
               putc(c,stdout);
               fclose(fp);            }
     return(0);
}
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Before we go on, perhaps a quick recap of the program development cycle is in
order. The steps in writing a program are:-
    1. Design your program (using pencil, paper & brain)
    2. Write & type in your source code ( with your favourite editor - mine
       is MicroEmacs, yours may be different ).
    3. Check, correct and SAVE your source code.
    4. Compile your program; if the compiler reports any errors, go back
       to 3.
    5. Test your program; if it doesn't work go back to 3 ( or 1, if you've
       really made a mess of it - you won't be the first! ).

Ok, back to CAT. I think the sensible way to organise things when programming
is to keep a separate directory per program, holding the source and object
programs and the associated documentation - you wouldn't dream of writing a
program without documenting it, would you? So first, create such a directory:
    md cat
followed by:
    cd cat
to make it your current working directory.
To get the program into the machine, we invoke the editor:
    me cat.c
'me' tells the shell to load the MicroEmacs program 'me.ttp', which it finds
on the RAM disc D, as explained earlier; 'cat.c' tells me.ttp that the file to
be edited is called cat.c, in the current directory. ( If it wasn't, you'd
have to be specific about where it was, as in 'me b:\dir2\fred.c' ). There is
nothing magic about the filename cat.c - its simply convention to give C
source programs a .c extension, and the name of the source doesn't have to
relate to the name of the finished program, so if you want to be silly you can
keep the source of jim.prg in fred.pic.
Since cat.c doesn't exist yet, Emacs will warn you "new file" at the bottom of
a blank screen, and let you get on with typing it in. On subsequent edits, it
will read in the file for you to amend. To save the file and leave the editor,
type control and z together; remember you MUST save the file, the compiler
reads it from disk, not from memory.
While on the subject of editing source programs, I have had queries about
program layout - where you need new lines, what spacing is needed etc.
Frankly, the compiler hardly gives a damn. Most of the pretty spacing is for
the human reader, to make the program structure easier to follow. Be warned
that the human eye can be deceived into seeing a structure that the compiler
can't: in particular check that things that should come in twos do so, like (
and ), { and }, " and ", ' and ', /* and */. If these all check out, look out
for missing ';'s at the end of statements  - and finally don't confuse = and
==. If you avoid all these pitfalls, you'll avoid 95% of C errors, and be a
better man than I. Back to the program.
When you're satisfied the program is correct, type control/z (ie hold dowm
control with one finger while you tap z with the other ) to save the program.

Version 2.1 of MJC includes a 'make' utility for automating the actual
compilation process. Here I have to own up and admit I haven't fully got to
grips with make yet, and all my developments to date have been done with the
MKP/MKT shell scripts used in version 1, updated where necessary. If you want
to get ahead of me, refer to the README supplied with 2.1 and try it out;  I
suspect however that you may find you need a 1 meg ST to make real use of
make.
For the time being, type the command:
    mkt cat
not, repeat not, mkt cat.c - I'll explain why later.
mkt is another shell script, which when expanded by the shell contains the
following command lines:-
    d:cc -id: -od:yc.out cat.c
    d:as d:ttp.s d:yc.out -l d:lib.a
    rm cat.ttp d:yc.out
    ren ya.out cat.ttp
Line 1 invokes the MJC compiler,cc; this reads your source file cat.c, and,
assuming it finds no errors, generates an intermediate file which it usually
calls yc.out. The -i option can specify a path to be searched for #include
files, and -o a name for the intermediate output file. This is a text file,
containing the source program converted to a macro-assembler format which is
(as far as I am aware) unique to this compiler. (However AS.DOC on L.05 does
describe the format, so if anyone out there fancies producing an A-line
interface for MJC, it's at least possible now.) If there are errors, they will
be listed on the screen. The error messages tend to be obscure, so expect to
be baffled; however they tell you which line number has thrown the compiler,
which is usually a clue, although certain errors aren't detected until the
actual line at fault has been passed so be prepared to step back through the
program.

Line 2 calls the assembler-linker as, which turns the intermediate code in
yc.out into a machine-code program called ya.out. The basic format of the
command line is
    as 'list of intermediate modules' -L 'list of libraries'
There will always be at least two intermediate modules, one of them being your
own yc.out, and before it a 'startup file' - in this case ttp.s. All ttp.s
does is allocate some workspace for the final program to run, and call some
initialisation routines that will be needed by your program, among them being
the allocation of standard input and output as described earlier.
There will invariably be at least one library after the -L; in this case
lib.a, which as mentioned earlier contains the code for routines like getc,
putc and printf.

Line 3 is easy - it deletes yc.out, which you don't need any more, and any
cat.ttp which might exist from an earlier compilation. If you had mistakenly
typed 'mkt cat.c' as your initial command, this line would be expanded to 'rm
yc.out cat.c.ttp', and the system would make a bad guess and delete cat.c -
and you wouldn't want that to happen to you the way it did to me.

Line 4, to round things off, renames ya.out to be your final program cat.ttp.

If everything went through without error, you can test the final program by
typing any of the cat example commands described earlier and smiling smugly
when they work.



















